    <section>
      <h2>Why Old Orchard Beach?</h2>
      <p>Old Orchard Beach is a premier tourist destination with 8,000+ year-round residents and 100,000+ summer visitors annually. The summer tourist population creates exceptional seasonal revenue opportunity. Unlike Portland's saturated market or Saco's modest traffic, OOB sits in a sweet spot: enough permanent residents to sustain baseline operations, with a tourist surge that can multiply revenue by 3-5x from May through September.</p>
      <p>The town's identity as a beach resort means visitors arrive with disposable income and vacation mindset. They are not price-shopping. They want quality, consistency, and a comfortable purchasing experience. For dispensary operators, this translates to higher average transaction values and less negotiation pressure than you'd encounter in a typical adult-use market.</p>
      <p>The competitive landscape is equally compelling. With only one to two existing dispensaries serving the entire seasonal population, the market is significantly under-served. A well-positioned dispensary on Portland Avenue or Route 1 can capture tourist traffic that currently has limited options.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Regulatory Framework</h2>
      <p>Old Orchard Beach dispensaries operate under Maine's adult-use cannabis regulations, governed by the Office of Cannabis Policy (OCP) under <a href="https://www.mainelegislature.org/legis/statutes/28-b/title28-Bsec201.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">M.R.S. Title 28-B, Section 201</a>. All retail dispensaries must obtain an Adult-Use Retail License from the OCP before commencing operations.</p>
      <h3>Local Licensing Requirements</h3>
      <p>In addition to the state license, Old Orchard Beach requires a local marijuana retail permit. The town charges an annual fee of $2,000-2,500 for this local authorization. Operators should budget for both the state application fee ($1,000 for new licenses) and the annual local renewal.</p>
      <h3>Zoning and Distance Requirements</h3>
      <p>Under <a href="https://www.mainelegislature.org/legis/statutes/28-b/title28-Bsec301.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">M.R.S. Title 28-B, Section 301</a>, dispensaries must maintain a minimum 500-foot buffer from schools, licensed childcare facilities, and public playgrounds. This requirement significantly narrows available commercial real estate in OOB's dense beachfront district.</p>
      <p>Old Orchard Beach designates commercial zones along Portland Avenue, the Old Orchard Street corridor, and parts of Route 1 where dispensary operations are permitted by-right or by special exception. Prospective operators should verify exact parcel eligibility with the town's Code Enforcement Officer before executing any lease agreement.</p>
    </section>

    <Callout title="Tourist Season Opportunity" type="passion">
      Old Orchard Beach is THE summer cannabis destination in southern Maine. If you can handle the seasonality — and it's a real swing — summer months can generate a full year's revenue. Come fall, it's quiet. But those July and August numbers can make up for it.
    </Callout>

