    <section>
      <h2>Local X-Factor: The Tourist Premium</h2>
      <p><strong>What sets OOB apart:</strong> Summer tourists—many from states without legal cannabis—eagerly visit Maine dispensaries. They pay premium prices without comparison shopping.</p>
      <p><strong>Strategic Implication:</strong> Stock premium products. Tourist customers prioritize quality and convenience over price. Plan staffing for July-August peak.</p>
      <p>The tourist premium manifests in several measurable ways. Visitor transactions at OOB-area dispensaries average 15-25% higher than at comparable Portland locations. Tourists purchase more concentrate products, edibles, and premium flower—categories with higher margins. They also show lower price sensitivity on brand-name products.</p>
      <p>The geographic advantage compounds this. OOB sits 14 miles from Portland and 3 miles from Saco. Tourists staying in OOB vacation rentals often lack transportation to reach Portland dispensaries. When they want cannabis, they look for the nearest option. A visible, accessible dispensary on Portland Avenue captures this trapped demand.</p>
      <h3>Capturing Tourist Traffic</h3>
      <p>Dispensary design matters significantly in this market. Ground-floor visibility with clear signage drives impulse visits. Tourist customers do not plan cannabis purchases the way locals do. They respond to proximity and convenience. A location near the pier, beach parking, or the Amtrak station captures visitors who did not plan to purchase but encounter an opportunity.</p>
      <p>Extended summer hours—until 10pm or later during peak season—align with tourist activity patterns. Most OOB tourists are still awake and active well past sunset during July and August. Matching this schedule captures revenue that competitors with standard 8pm closings leave on the table.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Startup Economics</h2>
      <p>Opening a dispensary in Old Orchard Beach requires capital investment of $300,000-400,000 for a standard 800-1,200 square foot retail location. This breaks down across several categories that operators should budget carefully.</p>
      <h3>Real Estate and Tenant Improvement</h3>
      <p>Commercial lease rates in OOB range from $16-24 per square foot annually depending on location. A 1,000 square foot space costs approximately $16,000-24,000 per year or $1,300-2,000 monthly. Tenant improvement costs for a dispensary buildout—including security systems, display cases, point-of-sale infrastructure, and compliance-mandated ventilation—typically run $75-125 per square foot.</p>
      <p>The 500-foot school buffer requirement limits available parcels significantly. Many ground-floor commercial spaces in the beachfront district fall within restricted zones near the elementary school on Ross Road. Route 1 properties north of the school zone offer more options with slightly lower rents.</p>
      <h3>Licensing and Compliance</h3>
      <p>State licensing fees total approximately $1,500-2,000 annually for the Adult-Use Retail License and associated renewals. Local permit fees add $2,000-2,500 annually. Security system installation, required under <a href="https://www.mainelegislature.org/legis/statutes/28-b/title28-Bsec401.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">M.R.S. Title 28-B, Section 401</a>, typically costs $15,000-25,000 for a comprehensive camera, alarm, and access control system.</p>
      <h3>Inventory and Operating Capital</h3>
      <p>Initial inventory for a new dispensary runs $50,000-80,000 depending on product mix and planned depth of selection. Maine's adult-use market requires all products to originate from licensed cultivators and manufacturers. Building relationships with regional wholesalers before opening ensures adequate initial stock and favorable pricing.</p>
      <p>Operators should maintain 60-90 days of operating capital (approximately $40,000-60,000) to cover payroll, rent, utilities, and compliance costs while waiting for regulatory approval, which can take 90-180 days from application submission to license issuance.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Seasonal Strategy</h2>
      <p>Old Orchard Beach's extreme seasonality is both the market's greatest challenge and its primary opportunity. Successful operators design their entire business model around the summer surge and winter lull.</p>
      <h3>May Through September: Maximizing the Surge</h3>
      <p>Tourist season drives 60-70% of annual revenue at OOB-area dispensaries. Staffing should anticipate 3-5x normal traffic during July and August. This means cross-training front-of-house staff, securing seasonal employees by April, and negotiating flexible lease terms that allow temporary expansion of retail space if viable.</p>
      <p>Inventory planning must account for the shift in customer preferences. Tourists purchase more premium eighths, concentrated extracts, and edible products than locals. A product mix weighted toward these categories during summer months captures higher margins. Pre-orders and online menu systems reduce in-store wait times during peak hours.</p>
      <h3>October Through April: Surviving the Quiet</h3>
      <p>Year-round resident traffic during winter months drops to 20-30% of summer levels. Operators should use this period for staff training, store improvements, and community relationship building. Many successful OOB dispensaries host local events during winter—industry meetups, educational workshops, or partnerships with local businesses—to maintain customer engagement.</p>
      <p>Fixed costs become critical during low-revenue months. Negotiating favorable lease terms with six months of reduced rent or percentage-of-sales clauses can mean the difference between profitability and closure. Operators who sign standard annual leases at peak-season rates often struggle through winter.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
