      <h3>Portland Avenue Analysis</h3>
      <p>Portland Avenue carries the highest tourist traffic and commands premium rents. Properties here benefit from foot traffic generated by beach visitors, pier attractions, and the amusement district. However, summer parking becomes constrained, and commercial lease rates reflect the premium location. A 1,000 square foot space on Portland Avenue runs $20,000-24,000 annually.</p>
      <p>The competitive visibility on Portland Avenue is valuable for brand building. Tourists who visit your dispensary often share the experience through reviews and social media. A prominent Portland Avenue location generates organic marketing value that extends beyond direct sales.</p>
      <h3>Route 1 Strategic Value</h3>
      <p>Route 1 properties offer the best combination of year-round accessibility and lower occupancy costs. The road carries consistent traffic from both local residents and tourists passing through en route to other destinations. Parking is more available than in the beachfront district, making it convenient for customers who drive.</p>
      <p>The 500-foot school buffer affects Route 1 parcels differently depending on proximity to the elementary school on Ross Road. North of the school, several commercial properties clear the buffer requirement and offer 1,200-2,000 square foot spaces suitable for dispensary operations at rents below Portland Avenue rates.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Staffing and Operations</h2>
      <p>A dispensary in Old Orchard Beach requires a small but skilled team. Maine's adult-use regulations require at least one licensed dispensary operator on-site during all hours of operation. Additional staff requirements scale with sales volume.</p>
      <h3>Core Team Structure</h3>
      <p>A typical OOB dispensary operates with 4-6 employees during peak season: one licensed manager, two to three budtenders on rotating shifts, one security guard (required during all open hours under <a href="https://www.mainelegislature.org/legis/statutes/28-b/title28-Bsec402.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">M.R.S. Title 28-B, Section 402</a>), and one inventory/management role. Winter months can reduce to two to three staff covering basic operating hours.</p>
      <h3>Recruiting for Seasonality</h3>
      <p>Hiring should begin in February and March for the following summer season. University students home for summer break represent a strong candidate pool in the greater Portland area. Experienced budtenders from Portland dispensaries sometimes seek seasonal work in OOB for the summer tourist volume and higher tips.</p>
      <p>Retention through winter requires intentional culture building. Staff who feel connected to the business and local community more often stay through quiet months. Some operators offer slightly higher winter wages or schedule flexibility to maintain a stable year-round team.</p>
    </section>

